          "body": "Jeremiah is 'restricted' — the Hebrew *atsar* suggests he is under some form of official prohibition from entering the Temple precincts, likely due to his earlier Temple Sermon (Jer. 7, 26) which had already cost him nearly his life. Unable to go himself, he commissions Baruch the son of Neriah as the scroll's public reader. Baruch is more than a secretary in this chapter; he is the prophetic deputy who risks public exposure in the very precincts where Jeremiah is banned. What the text notes without elaboration is significant: Baruch 'did according to all that Jeremiah the prophet commanded him' (36:8). The obedience is total and unqualified. For a scribe — a professional man with his own social standing and reputation — to stand in the Temple gate and read an oracle of judgment to a fasting public required moral courage. Baruch becomes one of the Old Testament's quiet models of faithful obedience: not the prophet, not the king, but the secretary who did what he was told when it cost something."
