          "title": "The burning — contempt with a scribe's knife (36:21-26)",
          "body": "Jehoiakim's burning of the scroll is one of the most theologically loaded acts in the Old Testament narrative literature. The text's detail is surgical: the king is in the winter house (private, comfortable), a fire burns before him in a brazier (warmth and convenience), and as Jehudi reads three or four columns, Jehoiakim cuts them with a scribe's knife and throws them into the fire — methodically, deliberately, column by column, 'until all the scroll was consumed' (36:23). This is not a rage; it is a procedure. The king does not lose control; he exercises it. And the narrator supplies the explicit verdict in verse 24: 'Yet the king and all his servants who heard all these words were not afraid, nor did they rend their garments.' The deliberate comparison to Josiah (2 Kings 22:11) — who tore his garments when the law scroll was read and wept before God — is inescapable. Father and son heard scrolls read in the same royal tradition and responded in precisely opposite ways. Josiah's response produced revival; Jehoiakim's response produces only condemnation. The word 'rend their garments' is the chapter's test of true hearing: the king who does not tear his robe when he hears the word of divine judgment has decided in advance that the word does not apply to him."
