        "excerpt": "When they had heard all the words, they turned in fear one to another and said to Baruch, 'We will surely report all these words to the king.'",
        "body": "The public reading of the scroll in the Temple precincts during a national fast (36:9-10) places the word of God in its most favorable possible hearing context: a solemn assembly, covenant people gathered, a day explicitly set apart for supplication before the LORD. Baruch reads from the chamber of Gemariah son of Shaphan — a family with prophetic sympathies; Shaphan himself had read the law scroll to Josiah (2 Kings 22:10). The setting is as favorable as it could be. And yet the text records no repentance. The silence is eloquent.\n\nMicaiah son of Gemariah hears the scroll and immediately reports to the officials in the palace (36:11-13). His action sets the chain in motion: officials summon Baruch, hear the scroll read a second time, and respond with fear (36:16). The word *pachad* — to tremble, to be seized with dread — is the chapter's own assessment of the officials' response. The word of God struck them. They took it seriously. But fear that does not produce obedience eventually routes itself into bureaucratic procedure: 'We will surely report all these words to the king.' The word is forwarded upward rather than acted upon downward. The officials become the word's messengers to royal power, not its agents of covenant renewal.\n\nThe officials' counsel to Baruch and Jeremiah to hide themselves (36:19) is a mixed signal. It shows they anticipated Jehoiakim's violent response — they knew their king well enough to fear for the messenger. This is a form of compassion, even of moral sympathy. But it is not obedience. They do not intercede before reading the scroll to the king; they do not use their own authority to act on the word's demands. Their fear of the word is real; their fear of the king is greater. Calvin's observation on this passage is sharp: 'Many there are who, being touched with a sense of God's judgment, yet flee to the king as a refuge and bring the word of God into contempt by subjecting it to human evaluation.'\n\nThis middle section of the chapter maps the vast territory between faithful obedience (Baruch, 36:8) and willful contempt (Jehoiakim, 36:23). Most people — most hearers of the word — inhabit this territory: genuinely alarmed, privately sympathetic, unwilling to suppress the word entirely, but equally unwilling to let the word actually govern their conduct or override their political calculations. The officials are not villains; they are the chapter's most uncomfortably recognizable characters.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pachad* (fear, 36:16) — the same word negated in 36:24 of the king. The officials' fear and the king's fearlessness use the same vocabulary, creating an explicit contrast the narrator has engineered. *Nagad* (to declare, report) — appears at 36:13, 16, 20: the word moves by reporting until it reaches the king, where reporting ends in burning."
